<li><a href="http://kyushu.com/gleaner/editorspick/seppuku.shtml" class="external text" title="http://kyushu.com/gleaner/editorspick/seppuku.shtml" rel="nofollow">Seppuku</a> - A Practical Guide (tongue-in-cheek)</li>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFBrinckmann2006">Brinckmann, Hans (2006-07-02). <a href="http://www.habri.co.uk/PerspectiveHfd_1_6.html#suicide" class="external text" title="http://www.habri.co.uk/PerspectiveHfd_1_6.html#suicide" rel="nofollow">"Japanese Society and Culture in Perspective: 6. Suicide, the Dark Shadow"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.habri.co.uk/PerspectiveHfd_1_6.html#suicide" class="external free" title="http://www.habri.co.uk/PerspectiveHfd_1_6.html#suicide" rel="nofollow">http://www.habri.co.uk/PerspectiveHfd_1_6.html#suicide</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Japanese+Society+and+Culture+in+Perspective%3A++6.+Suicide%2C+the+Dark+Shadow&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Brinckmann&amp;rft.aufirst=Hans&amp;rft.au=Brinckmann%2C+Hans&amp;rft.date=2006-07-02&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.habri.co.uk%2FPerspectiveHfd_1_6.html%23suicide&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Seppuku"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFFreeman-Mitford1871">Freeman-Mitford, Algernon Bertram (1871). "<a href="http://www.munseys.com/disktwo/tajadex.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.munseys.com/disktwo/tajadex.htm" rel="nofollow">An Account of the Hara-Kiri</a>". <i>Tales of Old Japan</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.munseys.com/disktwo/tajadex.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.munseys.com/disktwo/tajadex.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.munseys.com/disktwo/tajadex.htm</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=An+Account+of+the+Hara-Kiri&amp;rft.jtitle=Tales+of+Old+Japan&amp;rft.aulast=Freeman-Mitford&amp;rft.aufirst=Algernon+Bertram&amp;rft.au=Freeman-Mitford%2C+Algernon+Bertram&amp;rft.date=1871&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.munseys.com%2Fdisktwo%2Ftajadex.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Seppuku"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.win.net/ratsnest/archive-articles21/fog0000000384.html" class="external text" title="http://www.win.net/ratsnest/archive-articles21/fog0000000384.html" rel="nofollow">"The Fine Art of Seppuku"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.win.net/ratsnest/archive-articles21/fog0000000384.html" class="external free" title="http://www.win.net/ratsnest/archive-articles21/fog0000000384.html" rel="nofollow">http://www.win.net/ratsnest/archive-articles21/fog0000000384.html</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=The+Fine+Art+of+Seppuku&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.win.net%2Fratsnest%2Farchive-articles21%2Ffog0000000384.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Seppuku"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li><a href="http://www.zuihoden.com/" class="external text" title="http://www.zuihoden.com/" rel="nofollow">Zuihoden</a> - The mausoleum of <a href="/wiki/Date_Masamune" title="Date Masamune">Date Masamune</a> -- When he died, twenty of his followers killed themselves to serve him in the next life. They lay in state at Zuihoden</li>
<li>Seppuku and "cruel punishments" at the end of Tokugawa Shogunate <a href="http://turandot.ish-lyon.cnrs.fr/Artworks.php?ID=168" class="external autonumber" title="http://turandot.ish-lyon.cnrs.fr/Artworks.php?ID=168" rel="nofollow">[3]</a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.uni-erfurt.de/ostasiatische_geschichte/texte/japan/dokumente/17/tokugawa_legislation/index_files/buke_shohatto_1663.html" class="external text" title="http://www.uni-erfurt.de/ostasiatische_geschichte/texte/japan/dokumente/17/tokugawa_legislation/index_files/buke_shohatto_1663.html" rel="nofollow">Tokugawa Shogunate edict banning Junshi (Following one's lord in death)</a> From the Buke Sho Hatto (1663 AD) --</li>
</ul>
<dl>
<dd>"That the custom of following a master in death is wrong and unprofitable is a caution which has been at times given of old; but, owing to the fact that it has not actually been prohibited, the number of those who cut their belly to follow their lord on his decease has become very great. For the future, to those retainers who may be animated by such an idea, their respective lords should intimate, constantly and in very strong terms, their disapproval of the custom. If, notwithstanding this warning, any instance of the practice should occur, it will be deemed that the deceased lord was to blame for unreadiness. Henceforward, moreover, his son and successor will be held to be blameworthy for incompetence, as not having prevented the suicides."</dd>
</dl>
<ul>
<li><cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFFuse1980">Fuse, Toyomasa (1980). <a href="http://www.springerlink.com/content/n228553h733l5775/fulltext.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.springerlink.com/content/n228553h733l5775/fulltext.pdf" rel="nofollow">"Suicide and Culture in Japan: a study of seppuku as an institutionalized form of suicide"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.springerlink.com/content/n228553h733l5775/fulltext.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.springerlink.com/content/n228553h733l5775/fulltext.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.springerlink.com/content/n228553h733l5775/fulltext.pdf</a></span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Suicide+and+Culture+in+Japan%3A+a+study+of+seppuku+as+an+institutionalized+form+of+suicide&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Fuse&amp;rft.aufirst=Toyomasa&amp;rft.au=Fuse%2C+Toyomasa&amp;rft.date=1980&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.springerlink.com%2Fcontent%2Fn228553h733l5775%2Ffulltext.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Seppuku"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ul>


